# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardware-security-module
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:hardware-security-module/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The **Federal Information Processing Standard Publication 140-2**, (**FIPS PUB 140-2**), is a U.S. government computer security standard used to approve cryptographic modules.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The title is *Security Requirements for Cryptographic Modules*.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Initial publication was on May 25, 2001, and was last updated December 3, 2002.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Its successor, FIPS 140-3, was approved on March 22, 2019, and became effective on September 22, 2019.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] FIPS 140-3 testing began on September 22, 2020, and the first FIPS 140-3 validation certificates were issued in December 2022.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] FIPS 140-2 testing was still available until September 21, 2021 (later changed for applications already in progress to April 1, 2022), creating an overlapping transition period of more than one year.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] FIPS 140-2 test reports that remain in the CMVP queue will still be granted validations after that date, but all FIPS 140-2 validations will be moved to the Historical List on September 21, 2026 regardless of their actual final validation date.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued the FIPS 140 Publication Series to coordinate the requirements and standards for cryptography modules that include both hardware and software components.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Protection of a cryptographic module within a security system is necessary to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of the information protected by the module.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] This standard specifies the security requirements that will be satisfied by a cryptographic module.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The standard provides four increasing qualitative levels of security intended to cover a wide range of potential applications and environments.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The security requirements cover areas related to the secure design and implementation of a cryptographic module.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Federal agencies and departments can validate that the module in use is covered by an existing FIPS 140-1 or FIPS 140-2 certificate that specifies the exact module name, hardware, software, firmware, and/or applet version numbers.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The cryptographic modules are produced by the private sector or open source communities for use by the U.S. government and other regulated industries (such as financial and health-care institutions) that collect, store, transfer, share and disseminate sensitive but unclassified (SBU) information.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] A commercial cryptographic module is also commonly referred to as a hardware security module (HSM).
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] FIPS 140-2 defines four levels of security, simply named "Level 1" to "Level 4".
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] It does not specify in detail what level of security is required by any particular application.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Security Level 1 provides the lowest level of security.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Basic security requirements are specified for a cryptographic module (e.g., at least one Approved algorithm or Approved security function shall be used).
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] No specific physical security mechanisms are required in a Security Level 1 cryptographic module beyond the basic requirement for production-grade components.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] An example of a Security Level 1 cryptographic module is a personal computer (PC) encryption board.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] In addition to the tamper-evident physical security mechanisms required at Security Level 2, Security Level 3 attempts to prevent the intruder from gaining access to CSPs held within the cryptographic module.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Physical security mechanisms required at Security Level 3 are intended to have a high probability of detecting and responding to attempts at physical access, use or modification of the cryptographic module.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] The physical security mechanisms may include the use of strong enclosures and tamper-detection/response circuitry that zeroes all plaintext CSPs when the removable covers/doors of the cryptographic module are opened.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Security Level 4 provides the highest level of security.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] At this security level, the physical security mechanisms provide a complete envelope of protection around the cryptographic module with the intent of detecting and responding to all unauthorized attempts at physical access.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Penetration of the cryptographic module enclosure from any direction has a very high probability of being detected, resulting in the immediate deletion of all plaintext CSPs.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Security Level 4 cryptographic modules are useful for operation in physically unprotected environments.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Security Level 4 also protects a cryptographic module against a security compromise due to environmental conditions or fluctuations outside of the module's normal operating ranges for voltage and temperature.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Intentional excursions beyond the normal operating ranges may be used by an attacker to thwart a cryptographic module's defenses.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] For Levels 2 and higher, the operating platform upon which the validation is applicable is also listed.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Vendors do not always maintain their baseline validations.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Tamper evident FIPS 140-2 security labels are utilized to deter and detect tampering of modules.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] All of the tests under the CMVP are handled by third-party laboratories that are accredited as Cryptographic Module Testing laboratories by the National Voluntary Laboratory Accreditation Program (NVLAP).
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Vendors interested in validation testing may select any of the twenty-one accredited labs.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] NVLAP accredited Cryptographic Modules Testing laboratories perform validation testing of cryptographic modules.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Cryptographic modules are tested against requirements found in FIPS PUB 140–2, Security Requirements for Cryptographic Modules.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Security requirements cover 11 areas related to the design and implementation of a cryptographic module.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Within most areas, a cryptographic module receives a security level rating (1–4, from lowest to highest), depending on what requirements are met.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] For other areas that do not provide for different levels of security, a cryptographic module receives a rating that reflects fulfillment of all of the requirements for that area.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] 2. the fulfillment of all the requirements in the other areas.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] On a vendor's validation certificate, individual ratings are listed, as well as the overall rating.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] NIST maintains validation lists for all of its cryptographic standards testing programs (past and present).
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] All of these lists are updated as new modules/implementations receive validation certificates from NIST and CSE.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Items on the FIPS 140-1 and FIPS 140-2 validation list reference validated algorithm implementations that appear on the algorithm validation lists.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] In addition to using a valid cryptographic module, encryption solutions are required to use cipher suites with approved algorithms or security functions established by the FIPS 140-2 Annex A to be considered FIPS 140-2 compliant.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Steven Marquess posted in 2009 that FIPS 140-2 validation could lead to incentives to keep vulnerabilities and other defects hidden.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] CMVP can decertify software in which vulnerabilities are found, but it can take a year to re-certify software if defects are found, so companies can be left without a certified product to ship.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] As an example, Marquess mentions a vulnerability that was found, publicised, and fixed in the FIPS-certified open-source derivative of OpenSSL, with the publication meaning that the OpenSSL derivative was decertified.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] This decertification hurt companies relying on the OpenSSL-derivative's FIPS certification.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] By contrast, companies that had renamed and certified a copy of the open-source OpenSSL derivative were not decertified, even though they were basically identical, and did not fix the vulnerability.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] Marquess therefore argues that the FIPS process inadvertently encourages hiding software's origins, to de-associate it from defects since found in the original, while potentially leaving the certified copy vulnerable.
[src:hardware-security-module/fips-140-2] In recent years, CMVP has taken steps to avoid the situation described by Marquess, moving validations to the Historical List based on the algorithms and functions contained in the module, rather than based on the provenance.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] A **hardware security module** (**HSM**) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages secrets (most importantly digital keys), and performs encryption and decryption functions for digital signatures, strong authentication and other cryptographic functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] HSMs may have features that provide tamper evidence such as visible signs of tampering or logging and alerting, or tamper resistance which makes tampering difficult without making the HSM inoperable, or tamper responsiveness such as deleting keys upon tamper detection.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Each module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips to prevent tampering and bus probing, or a combination of chips in a module that is protected by the tamper evident, tamper resistant, or tamper responsive packaging.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] A vast majority of existing HSMs are designed mainly to manage secret keys.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Many HSM systems have means to securely back up the keys they handle outside of the HSM.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Keys may be backed up in wrapped form and stored on a computer disk or other media, or externally using a secure portable device like a smartcard or some other security token.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] HSMs are used for real time authorization and authentication in critical infrastructure thus are typically engineered to support standard high availability models including clustering, automated failover, and redundant field-replaceable components.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] A few of the HSMs available in the market have the capability to execute specially developed modules within the HSM's secure enclosure.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Such an ability is useful, for example, in cases where special algorithms or business logic has to be executed in a secured and controlled environment.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] The modules can be developed in native C language, .NET, Java, or other programming languages.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Although the highest level of FIPS 140 security certification attainable is Security Level 4, most of the HSMs have Level 3 certification.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] In the Common Criteria system the highest EAL (Evaluation Assurance Level) is EAL7; most of the HSMs have EAL4+ certification.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] When used in financial payments applications, the security of an HSM is often validated against the HSM requirements defined by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module can be employed in any application that uses digital keys.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Typically, the keys would be of high value - meaning there would be a significant, negative impact to the owner of the key if it were compromised.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] HSMs are also deployed to manage transparent data encryption keys for databases and keys for storage devices such as disk or tape.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Some HSM systems are also hardware cryptographic accelerators.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] They usually cannot beat the performance of hardware-only solutions for symmetric key operations.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] However, with performance ranges from 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA signatures per second, HSMs can provide significant CPU offload for asymmetric key operations.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Since the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is recommending the use of 2,048 bit RSA keys from year 2010, performance at longer key sizes has become more important.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] To address this issue, most HSMs now support elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), which delivers stronger encryption with shorter key lengths.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] In PKI environments, the HSMs may be used by certification authorities (CAs) and registration authorities (RAs) to generate, store, and handle asymmetric key pairs.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] On the other hand, device performance in a PKI environment is generally less important, in both online and offline operations, as Registration Authority procedures represent the performance bottleneck of the Infrastructure.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Specialized HSMs are used in the payment card industry.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] HSMs support both general-purpose functions and specialized functions required to process transactions and comply with industry standards.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] They normally do not feature a standard API.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] The major organizations that produce and maintain standards for HSMs on the banking market are the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, ANS X9, and ISO.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Performance-critical applications that have to use HTTPS (SSL/TLS), can benefit from the use of an SSL Acceleration HSM by moving the RSA operations, which typically requires several large integer multiplications, from the host CPU to the HSM device.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Typical HSM devices can perform about 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA operations/second.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Some performance at longer key sizes is becoming increasingly important.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] An increasing number of registries use HSMs to store the key material that is used to sign large zonefiles.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] OpenDNSSEC is an open-source tool that manages signing DNS zone files.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] On January 27, 2007, ICANN and Verisign, with support from the U.S.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Department of Commerce, started deploying DNSSEC for DNS root zones.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Root signature details can be found on the Root DNSSEC's website.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Blockchain technology depends on cryptographic operations.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Safeguarding private keys is essential to maintain the security of blockchain processes that utilize asymmetric cryptography.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] The private keys are often stored in a cryptocurrency wallet like the hardware wallet in the image.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] The synergy between HSMs and blockchain is mentioned in several papers, emphasizing their role in securing private keys and verifying identity, e.g. in contexts such as blockchain-driven mobility solutions.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Automotive hardware security modules (HSMs) are embedded cryptographic coprocessors integrated into electronic control units (ECUs) to protect in-vehicle systems and communication buses against manipulation and misuse.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] They act as a hardware root of trust by securely generating and storing cryptographic keys and offloading security-critical operations such as secure boot, encryption, decryption, authentication and attestation.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] In modern ECU designs, HSMs are one of several hardware primitives that can underpin a hardware root of trust alongside secure elements, trusted platform modules (TPMs), one-time programmable (OTP) and read-only memories (ROM), and physical unclonable functions (PUFs).
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Their use provides dedicated hardware support for cryptographic operations, but also introduces trade-offs in die area, power consumption and latency, so they are typically integrated into mid- and high-end automotive domain controllers rather than the smallest microcontrollers.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Automotive HSMs are typically accompanied by dedicated firmware and software components that manage access to cryptographic services.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] These include HSM firmware, secure boot loaders, cryptographic libraries, and middleware that expose security services to the operating system and application software.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] In AUTOSAR-based systems, HSM firmware may interface with standardized service layers to provide cryptographic operations to applications.
[src:hardware-security-module/hardware-security-module] Commercial HSM firmware implementations are available from several automotive software vendors, often as components integrated into AUTOSAR platforms or OEM security frameworks.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:hardware-security-module/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A **secure cryptoprocessor** is a dedicated computer-on-a-chip or microprocessor for carrying out cryptographic operations, embedded in a packaging with multiple physical security measures, which give it a degree of tamper resistance.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Unlike cryptographic processors that output decrypted data onto a bus in a secure environment, a secure cryptoprocessor does not output decrypted data or decrypted program instructions in an environment where security cannot always be maintained.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The purpose of a secure cryptoprocessor is to act as the keystone of a security subsystem, eliminating the need to protect the rest of the subsystem with physical security measures.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module (HSM) contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] These devices are high grade secure cryptoprocessors used with enterprise servers.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module can have multiple levels of physical security with a single-chip cryptoprocessor as its most secure component.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The cryptoprocessor does not reveal keys or executable instructions on a bus, except in encrypted form, and zeros keys by attempts at probing or scanning.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The crypto chip(s) may also be potted in the hardware security module with other processors and memory chips that store and process encrypted data.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Any attempt to remove the potting will cause the keys in the crypto chip to be zeroed.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module may also be part of a computer (for example an ATM) that operates inside a locked safe to deter theft, substitution, and tampering.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Some secure cryptoprocessors can even run general-purpose operating systems such as Linux inside their security boundary.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Cryptoprocessors input program instructions in encrypted form and decrypt the instructions to plain instructions, which are then executed within the same cryptoprocessor chip where the decrypted instructions are inaccessibly stored.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] By never revealing the decrypted program instructions, the cryptoprocessor prevents tampering of programs by technicians who may have legitimate access to the sub-system data bus.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Data processed by a cryptoprocessor is also frequently encrypted.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is an implementation of a secure cryptoprocessor that brings the notion of trusted computing to ordinary PCs by enabling a secure environment.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Present TPM implementations focus on providing a tamper-proof boot environment, and persistent and volatile storage encryption.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Security chips for embedded systems are also available that provide the same level of physical protection for keys and other secret material as a smartcard processor or TPM but in a smaller, less complex and less expensive package.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] They are often referred to as cryptographic authentication devices and are used to authenticate peripherals, accessories and/or consumables.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Like TPMs, they are usually turnkey integrated circuits intended to be embedded in a system, usually soldered to a PC board.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Secure cryptoprocessors, while useful, are not invulnerable to attack, particularly for well-equipped and determined opponents (e.g. a government intelligence agency) who are willing to expend enough resources on the project.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] One attack on a secure cryptoprocessor targeted the IBM 4758.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] A team at the University of Cambridge reported the successful extraction of secret information from an IBM 4758, using a combination of mathematics, and special-purpose codebreaking hardware.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] However, this attack was not practical in real-world systems because it required the attacker to have full access to all API functions of the device.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Normal and recommended practices use the integral access control system to split authority so that no one person could mount the attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Smartcards are significantly more vulnerable, as they are more open to physical attack.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Additionally, hardware backdoors can undermine security in smartcards and other cryptoprocessors unless investment is made in anti-backdoor design methods.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] This would require both physical possession of the device as well as skills and equipment beyond that of most technical personnel.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Other attack methods involve carefully analyzing the timing of various operations that might vary depending on the secret value or mapping the current consumption versus time to identify differences in the way that '0' bits are handled internally vs.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Or the attacker may apply temperature extremes, excessively high or low clock frequencies or supply voltage that exceeds the specifications in order to induce a fault.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The internal design of the cryptoprocessor can be tailored to prevent these attacks.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The first single-chip cryptoprocessor design was for copy protection of personal computer software (see US Patent 4,168,396, Sept 18, 1979) and was inspired by Bill Gates's Open Letter to Hobbyists.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The hardware security module (HSM), a type of secure cryptoprocessor, was invented by Egyptian-American engineer Mohamed M.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] He invented a high security module dubbed the "Atalla Box" which encrypted PIN and ATM messages, and protected offline devices with an un-guessable PIN-generating key.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] In 1972, he filed a patent for the device.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] He founded Atalla Corporation (now Utimaco Atalla) that year, and commercialized the "Atalla Box" the following year, officially as the Identikey system.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was a card reader and customer identification system, consisting of a card reader console, two customer PIN pads, intelligent controller and built-in electronic interface package.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It allowed the customer to type in a secret code, which is transformed by the device, using a microprocessor, into another code for the teller.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] During a transaction, the customer's account number was read by the card reader.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was a success, and led to the wide use of high security modules.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Fearful that Atalla would dominate the market, banks and credit card companies began working on an international standard in the 1970s.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The IBM 3624, launched in the late 1970s, adopted a similar PIN verification process to the earlier Atalla system.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Atalla was an early competitor to IBM in the banking security market.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] At the National Association of Mutual Savings Banks (NAMSB) conference in January 1976, Atalla unveiled an upgrade to its Identikey system, called the Interchange Identikey.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It added the capabilities of processing online transactions and dealing with network security.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Designed with the focus of taking bank transactions online, the Identikey system was extended to shared-facility operations.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was consistent and compatible with various switching networks, and was capable of resetting itself electronically to any one of 64,000 irreversible nonlinear algorithms as directed by card data information.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] The Interchange Identikey device was released in March 1976.
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Later in 1979, Atalla introduced the first network security processor (NSP).
[src:hardware-security-module/secure-cryptoprocessor] Atalla's HSM products protect 250 million card transactions every day as of 2013, and secure the majority of the world's ATM transactions as of 2014.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance ranges from simple features like screws with special drives and tamper-evident seals to more complex devices that render themselves inoperable or encrypt all data transmissions between individual chips, use of materials needing special tools and knowledge.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant devices or features are common on packages to deter package or product tampering or enable its detection.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Anti-tamper devices have one or more components: tamper resistance, tamper detection, tamper response, and tamper evidence.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In some applications, devices are only tamper-evident rather than tamper-resistant.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tampering involves the deliberate altering or adulteration of a product, package, or system.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Solutions may involve all phases of product production, packaging, distribution, logistics, sale, and use.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] No single solution can be considered as "tamper-proof".
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Often multiple levels of security need to be addressed to reduce the risk of tampering.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Some devices contain non-standard screws or bolts in an attempt to deter access.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Examples are telephone switching cabinets (which have triangular bolt heads that a hex socket fits), or bolts with 5-sided heads used to secure doors to outdoor electrical distribution transformers.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] A standard Torx screw head can be made in a tamper-resistant form with a pin in the center, which excludes standard Torx drivers.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Various other security screw heads have been devised to discourage casual access to the interior of such devices as consumer electronics.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] This style of tamper resistance is most commonly found in burglar alarms.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Most trip devices (e.g. pressure pads, passive infrared sensors (motion detectors), door switches) use two signal wires that, depending on configuration, are normally open or normally closed.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] The sensors sometimes need power, so to simplify cable runs, multi-core cable is used.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] While 4 cores is normally enough for devices that require power (leaving two spare for those that don't), cable with additional cores can be used.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] These additional cores can be wired into a special so-called "tamper circuit" in the alarm system.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper circuits are monitored by the system to give an alarm if a disturbance to devices or wiring is detected.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Enclosures for devices and control panels may be fitted with anti-tamper switches.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Would-be intruders run the risk of triggering the alarm by attempting to circumvent a given device.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Sensors such as movement detectors, tilt detectors, air-pressure sensors, light sensors, etc., which might be employed in some burglar alarms, might also be used in a bomb to hinder defusing.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Nearly all appliances and accessories can only be opened with the use of a tool.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] This is intended to prevent casual or accidental access to energized or hot parts, or damage to the equipment.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Manufacturers may use tamper-resistant screws, which cannot be unfastened with common tools.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant screws are used on electrical fittings in many public buildings to reduce tampering or vandalism that may cause a danger to others.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] A user who breaks equipment by modifying it in a way not intended by the manufacturer might deny they did it, in order to claim the warranty or (mainly in the case of PCs) call the helpdesk for help in fixing it.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-evident seals may be enough to deal with this.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] However, they cannot easily be checked remotely, and many countries have statutory warranty terms that mean manufacturers may still have to service the equipment.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper proof screws will stop most casual users from tampering in the first place.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In the US, the Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act prevents manufacturers from voiding warranties solely due to tampering.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] A warranty may be dishonored only if the tampering actually affected the part that has failed, and could have caused the failure.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant microprocessors are used to store and process private or sensitive information, such as private keys or electronic money credit.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] To prevent an attacker from retrieving or modifying the information, the chips are designed so that the information is not accessible through external means and can be accessed only by the embedded software, which should contain the appropriate security measures.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Examples of tamper-resistant chips include all secure cryptoprocessors, such as the IBM 4758 and chips used in smartcards, as well as the Clipper chip.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper-resistant chips may be designed to zeroise their sensitive data (especially cryptographic keys) if they detect penetration of their security encapsulation or out-of-specification environmental parameters.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] A chip may even be rated for "cold zeroisation", the ability to zeroise itself even after its power supply has been crippled.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In addition, the custom-made encapsulation methods used for chips used in some cryptographic products may be designed in such a manner that they are internally pre-stressed, so the chip will fracture if interfered with.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Nevertheless, the fact that an attacker may have the device in their possession for as long as they like, and perhaps obtain numerous other samples for testing and practice, means that it is impossible to totally eliminate tampering by a sufficiently motivated opponent.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Because of this, one of the most important elements in protecting a system is overall system design.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In particular, tamper-resistant systems should "fail gracefully" by ensuring that compromise of one device does not compromise the entire system.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In this manner, the attacker can be practically restricted to attacks that cost more than the expected return from compromising a single device.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Since the most sophisticated attacks have been estimated to cost several hundred thousand dollars to carry out, carefully designed systems may be invulnerable in practice.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In the United States, purchasing specifications require anti-tamper (AT) features on military electronic systems.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Tamper resistance finds application in smart cards, set-top boxes and other devices that use digital rights management (DRM).
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In this case, the issue is not about stopping the user from breaking the equipment or hurting themselves, but about either stopping them from extracting codes, or acquiring and saving the decoded bitstream.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] This is usually done by having many subsystem features buried within each chip (so that internal signals and states are inaccessible) and by making sure the buses between chips are encrypted.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] DRM mechanisms also use certificates and asymmetric key cryptography in many cases.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] In all such cases, tamper resistance means not allowing the device user access to the valid device certificates or public-private keys of the device.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] The process of making software robust against tampering attacks is referred to as "software anti-tamper".
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Resistance to tampering can be built in or added to packaging.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] Software is also said to be tamper-resistant when it contains measures to make reverse engineering harder, or to prevent a user from modifying it against the manufacturer's wishes (such as removing a restriction on how it can be used).
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] One commonly used method is code obfuscation.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] However, effective tamper resistance in software is much harder than in hardware, as the software environment can be manipulated to near-arbitrary extent by the use of emulation.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] If implemented, trusted computing would make software tampering of protected programs at least as difficult as hardware tampering, as the user would have to hack the trust chip to give false certifications in order to bypass remote attestation and sealed storage.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] However, the current specification makes it clear that the chip is not expected to be tamper-proof against any reasonably sophisticated physical attack; that is, it is not intended to be as secure as a tamper-resistant device.
[src:hardware-security-module/tamper-resistance] That has the side effect that software maintenance gets more complex because software updates need to be validated, and errors in the upgrade process may lead to a false-positive triggering of the protection mechanism.
